column168: AT APPROXIMATELY 1845 HOURS ON DECEMBER 14, 1995 IN NIAGARA FALLS YARD, CONRAIL EMPLOYEES OBSERVED A FLAME THREE FEET HIGH SHOOT FROM THE MANWAY OF CAR DUPX 8835.  THE WEATHER WAS COLD AND HAD BEEN RAINING ALL DAY.  A TEAM FROM THE CONSIGNEE RESPONDED AND FOUND NO TRACE OF A FLAME OR LEAK. THIS INFORMATION WAS CONVEYED TO THE REPORTING OFFICE AND THE DETERMINATION MADE THAT A RELEASE HAD NOT OCCURED.  COPY OF DUPONT'S TRANSPORTATION INCIDENT REPORT OF THE INCIDENT.  IT STATES, IT PART, UPON PLACEMENT OF THE RAILCAR AT OUR PLANT, THEY (QUALIFIED PERSONNEL) OBSERVED A QUANTITY OF SODIUM RESIDUE CAKE ONTO THE EXTERIOR OF THE RAILCAR OCCASIONALLY REACTING WITH WATER OR SNOW ACCUMULATED ON THAT AREA OF THE RAILCAR JACKET.  "APPARENTLY RESIDUE SODIUM REMAINED IN THE MANWAY AREA FROM THE UNLOADING PROCESS AT ASARCO'S GLOVER, MO PLANT.  INCIDENT.  NOT A TRANSPORTATION INCIDENT.

I USED THE RESPONSE SHEET FOR LIQUID-1 SPRINKLED SODIUM BICARBONATE ONTO THE MATERIAL.  I USED PH TAPE AND KEPT ADDING THE SODIUM BICARBONATE UNTIL THE COLOR OF THE PH TAPE FELL IN THE 6-9 RANGE.  I ABSORBED THE REMAINING NEUTRALIZED LIQUID WITH SOLUSORB.  I PUT THE ABSORBED MATERIAL IN A PLASTIC BAG THEN PROCESSED THE WASTE THROUGH DMP.

column168: DRIVER WAS HEADING WEST ON DOMINION BLVD AT ABOUT 45 MPH (LEGAL LIMIT) AS HE APPROACHED THE INTERSECTION WITH VA ROUTE 190 WHICH WAS CONTROLLED BY A TRAFFIC SIGNAL.  THE LIGHT WAS GREEN AND AFTER SLOWING DOWN TO ABOUT 20 MPH THE DRIVER STARTED INTO A LEFT TURN ONTO ROUTE 190.  THE VEHICLE WAS ALMOST THROUGH THE TURN WHEN IT OVERTURNED ONTO ITS RIGHT SIDE, SKIDDED ABOUT TEN FEET AND STRUCK A CONCRETE CURB, WHICH IN TURN PUNCTURED A HOLE IN THE TANK - THAT PART OF THE TANK WHICH WAS SKIDDING ON THE HIGHWAY, LOWEST PART OF TANK.  THE RUPTURE WAS TOO LARGE TO IMMEDIATELY PLUG AND THE ENTIRE FRONT COMPARTMENT SPILLED.  OIL TRANSPORT INITIATED A SPECIAL TRAINING PROGRAM CONCERNING HIGH CENTER OF GRAVITY FOR TANKERS AND PROPER METHODS OF CORNERING.  THERE APPEARS TO BE NO NEED FOR PACKAGE IMPROVEMENTS OR MODIFICATIONS.

THEY DISCOVERED THAT A SMALL DRUM HAD TOP SMALL BUNG LOOSE. IT HAD ALLOWED LIQUID BROMINE TO COLLECT AROUND TOP OF DRUM (INSIDE RING). THEY REMOVED THE LEAKING DRUM AND PLACED IT IN A RECOVERY DRUM. SHIPPER WAS CALLED. THEY CAME AND PICKED UP LEAKING DRUM AND ALL MATERIALS USED IN CONTAINMENT AND CLEANUP. IT WAS ALSO DISCOVERED THAT A SEAL IN THE DRUM WAS LOOSE OR MISSING. WILL NEED FURTHER INSPECTION TO DETERMINE EXACT CAUSE. IT IS A POSSIBILITY THAT IT COULD HAVE GOTTEN HIT - THIS COULD HAVE KNOCKED THE BUNG LOOSE AND CAUSED THE SEAL TO FAIL, OR IT COULD HAVE BEEN DRUM FAILURE.
CUSTOMER'S UNLOADING OPERATOR UNHOOKED THE HOSE FROM THE TANK BEFORE DRIVER HAD PUMP OFF. SOME PRODUCT SPRAYED ON THE OPERATOR; HOWEVER, HE SUFFERED NO INJURY.

column168: A VAN TRAILER CONTAINING HAZARDOUS WASTE ENROUTE FROM THE COUNTY OF FAIRFAX, VA DEPARTMENT OF PUBLIC WORKS LOCATED AT 1200 GOVERNMENT CENTER PARKWAY IN FAIRFAX, VIRGINIA TO SPRING GROVE AVENUE IN CINCINNATI, OH. UPON ARRIVAL AT THE DISPOSAL FACILITY, IT WAS DISCOVERED THAT APPROXIMATELY 1 PINT OF MATERIAL HAD ESCAPED FROM THE TOP BUNG CAP OF ONE OF THE DRUMS ONTO THE FLOOR OF THE VAN TRAILER WHERE IT WAS PREVENTED FROM ESCAPING TO THE ENVIRONMENT.  FACILITY PERSONNEL IMMEDIATELY CONTAINED THE RELEASE, ABSORBED ALL FREE LIQUID WITH SPEEDI DRY, AND REPLACED THE GASKET ON THE BUNG CAP THAT HAD FAILED.  ALL CLEAN-UP DEBRIS GENERATED, AS A RESULT OF THIS INCIDENT WAS DISPOSED OF THROUGH THE INTENDED WASTE MANAGEMENT FACILITY.  PRIOR TO DEPARTURE FROM THE SHIPPER'S LOCATION, ALL CONTAINERS WERE INSPECTED AND NO EVIDENCE OF LEAKING WAS OBSERVED.  ALL LOADING PERSONNEL WILL CONTINUE TO INSPECT EACH CONTAINER AS IT IS LOADED AND WILL CONTINUE TO INSPECT EACH CLOSURE DEVICE TO INSURE A PROPER SEAL IN ACHIEVED.

A LEGAL WEIGHT OF UNDER 20 TONS WAS NOW LOADED.  THE SOIL ABOUT FIVE FEET, IN FRONT OF TAILGATE WAS SLIGHTLY WET.  DURING THE TRANSPORTATION, SOME OF THE WATER SEPARATED FROM THE SOIL AND FOUND ITS WAY UNDER THE PLASTIC LINER TO SEEP OUT OF THE TAILGATE.  1 VERY SMALL AMOUNT MADE IT TO THE PAVEMENT.  IT DID SOIL THE TAILLIGHT PANEL AND MUDFLAPS, BUT NOT ENOUGH TO EFFECT TAILLIGHTS OR THREE BAR MARKERS, THE WATER IN THE LOAD FROZE WITHIN 2 HOURS AND THE FOLLOWING MORNING; HARPER EMERGENCY RESPONSE TEAM OPENED THE TAILGATE, SHOVELED THE MUD FORWARD THEN RESEALED THE TAILGATE WITH TAPE & PLASTIC.

column168: OUR TRUCK WAS ENTERING ONTO HIGHWAY 2 FROM A NARROW SNOW COVERED APPROACH. HE SWUNG WIDE TO MAKE THE CORNER HOWEVER DUE TO THE SNOW COVER THE REAR TRAILER CAME TO CLOSE TO THE INSIDE DITCH AND SLID IN CAUSING THE REAR TRAILER TO OVERTURN.  THE TRACTOR AND FIRST TRAILER WAS BLOCKING HIGHWAY 2 WHEN THE SECOND TRAILER OVERTURNED.  NOTHING ON THE SECOND TRAILER WHICH WAS LOADED WITH 3500 GALLONS OF BLENDED DIESEL FUEL FAILED, HOWEVER THE DOME LID SEAL DID SEEP LESS THAN 10 GALLONS DUE TO THE PRESSURE OF THE PRODUCT ON THE DOME LID.  THE LOCAL FIRE DEPARTMENT AND MONTANA HIGHWAY PATROL RESPONDED HELPING WITH TRAFFIC CONTROL AND OFF LOADING THE OVERTURNED TRAILER SO IT COULD BE SET BACK UPRIGHT.  TRAFFIC WAS DETOURED AROUND THE VEHICLES WHILE THE TRAILER WAS BEING OFFLOADED AND SET BACK UPRIGHT AND THE ROADWAY CLEARED.  THE ROADWAY WAS BLOCKED WITH TRAFFIC REROUTED FOR APPROXIMATELY 6 HOURS WHILE THE TRAILER WAS PUMPED OFF AND THE ROADWAY CLEARED.  ALL RESPONDING AGENCIES COOPERATED WELL WITH EACH OTHER IN GETTING THE AREA CLEARED AND CLEANED UP AS QUICKLY AS POSSIBLE. ALL FUEL SPILLED WAS CLEANED UP AND PUT ON PLASTIC TO BE PROPERLY DISPOSED OF.  NO FURTHER ACTION IS EXPECTED AT THIS TIME.
FREIGHT PUT IN RECOVERY DRUM AND DELIVERED TO MACDERMIND  (THE ORIGINAL SHIPPER).

column168: THE INCIDENT OCCURED DUE TO FAILURE OF THE POLETHYLENE BLADDER OF THE INTERNAL CONTAINER NUMBERED 951130-LRCHJ-014 CAUSING THE HYDROGEN PEROXIDE TO COME INTO CONTACT WITH THE FIBER PORTION OF THE 21 P CONTAINER.  THE ENSUING CHEMICAL REACTION CAUSED SUFFICIENT PRESSURE TO SEPARATE THE LID OF THE OVERPACK FROM THE REST OF THE CONTAINER.  THE LID WAS THEN PROJECTED INTO THE TRAILER ROOF CAUSING A 12" TEAR IN THE ROOF.  THE EVOLVING HEAT OF THE REACTION CAUSED THE CHARRING OF THE INTERIOR WALL AND THE SUBSEQUENT BUCKLING OF THE OUTSIDE TRAILER WALL.  THE HEAT ALSO CAUSED A CHAIN REACTION WITH CONTAINER NUMER 951130-LRCHJ-013 WHICH MELTED AND RELEASED ITS CONTENTS TO THE SECONDARY CONTAINMENT OF THE TRAILER.  A THIRD CONTAINER NUMBERED 951130-LRCHJ-015 WAS DAMAGED BY THE HEAT.  WHILE BOTH THE FIBER DRUM AND OVERPACK WERE DAMAGED, THE OVERPACK MAINTAINED SUFFICIENT INTEGRITY TO CONTAIN ALL THE CONTENTS OF THE LOAD WAS VIRTUALLY UNDAMAGED.  IT WAS DECIDED THAT TO AVOID A REOCCURRENCE OF THIS INCIDENT THAT STRONG OXIDIZING SOLUTIONS WILL NO LONGER BE ACCEPTED FOR SHIPMENT IN FIBERBOARD CONTAINER.  FINALLY IT SHOULD BE NOTED THAT NO MATERIAL WAS RELEASED TO THE ENVIRONMENT AND NO INJURIES OCCURRED.  #35, 36 - DUE TO THERMAL DESTRUCTION OF INTERNAL DRUM NO OTHER MARKINGS WERE VISIBLE.

OUR CITY DRIVE BROUGHT BACK A SHIPMENT FROM NALCO CHEMICAL COMPANY WHICH CONSISTED OF 7 TOTES WHICH WERE ALL RESIDUE: LAST CONTAINED. HOWEVER, OUR DRIVER WAS COMPLAINING OF DIZZINESS AND IRRITATION OF THE EYES AND THROAT. THEY HAD HIM SIT DOWN AWAY FROM THE TRUCK FACING A BREEZE OF FRESH AIR & IMMEDIATELY CONTACTED THE SHIPPER WHO RESPONDED. AFTER THE CITY DRIVER WAS FEELING BETTER, HE WAS SENT TO THE BELLFLOWER MEDICAL CENTER IN BELL FLOWER, CA AT ABOUT 1825 AS A PRECAUTIONARY MEASURE. HE WAS RELEASED WITH INSTRUCTIONS TO REPORT AGAIN THE NEXT MORNING FOR A FOLLOW-UP. THE CITY DRIVER HAS A HISTORY OF SINUS PROBLEMS. THERE WAS NO ACTUAL LEAK, ONLY PRODUCT ON THE OUTSIDE OF THE CONTAINERS. THE SHIPPER REMOVED THE TOTES AND HANDLED THE INCIDENT IN DETAIL.

ON FLIGHT 8655 ENROUTE TO SAN LUIS OBISPO FROM ONTARIO, THE PILOT WENT ON OXYGEN AND DID NOT DECLARED AN EMERGENCY.  UPON LANDING, THE CARGO DOOR WAS OPENED AND THE SMELL DISSIPATED.  WEST AIR IS OUR FEEDER OPERATOR, THEIR AIRCRAFT MAINTENANCE HAVE RELEASED THE PLANE FOR SERVICE.  DUE TO THE HORRIBLE ODOR OF THE MATERIAL WE BELIEVE THAT THE MATERIAL SHOULD HAVE BEEN DECLARED AS AN OTHER REGULATED SUBSTANCE.  THERE WERE NO SHIPPING PAPERS NOR ANY MARKING OR LABELING ON THE BOX.  THE SHIPPER & FAA HAVE BEEN NOTIFIED.  THE FREIGHT IS BEING HELD FOR FAA INSPECTION.

AFTER THE PACKAGE WAS UNLOADED FROM THE VAN AND STAGED FOR INSPECTION, A SPILL WAS NOTICED.  IN ADDITION THERE ARE EXTREMELY NOXIOUS ODORS ASSOCIATED WITH THIS MATERIAL.  THE SPILLED MATERAIL WAS CLEANED UP AND ALONG WITH THE PACKAGE, THEY WERE PLACED IN A SALVAGE DRUM.  PER 1CA02-9-1, AN OTHER REGULATED SUBSTANCE IS ANY MATERIAL WHICH HAS AN ANAESTETIC, NOXIOUS, OR OTHER SIMILIAR PROPERTIES SUCH AS COULD CAUSE EXTREME ANNOYANCE OR DISCOMFORT TO A FLIGHT CREW MEMBER SO AS TO PREVENT THE CORRECT PERFORMANCE OF ASSIGNED DUTIES.  BASED ON THAT DEFINITION, THE FAA & SHIPPER WERE NOTIFIED.  THE FREIGHT IS BEING HELD FOR AN FAA INSPECTION.

THIS IS A STATEMENT CONCERNING THE MATERIAL LEAKAGE THAT OCCURED ON THE MORNING OF 12/12/95.  I LEFT THE AUGUSTA BRANCH AROUND 1230AM.  DURING MY PRETRIP INSPECTION ALL WAS OK IN MADISON GA.  THERE WERE NO PROBLEMS WITH THE TRUCK OR THE CARGO.  WHEN I ARRIVED AT THE BRANCH WITH THE TRUCK OR THE CARGO.  WHEN I ARRIVED AT THE BRANCH IN NORCROSS I SAW SEEPAGE COMING FROM THE TRAILER.  THE WASTE DRUMS THAT WE PICK UP FROM THIS CUSTOMER SOMETIMES COME WITH WATER ON TOP OF THEM.  WHEN I PULLED THE TRUCK INSIDE THE GATE I OPENED THE REAR DOOR AND SMELLED MATERIAL.  I GOT MY MASK OUT OF THE SPILL BOX IN THE TRUCK AND GOT INTO THE TRAILER TO INSPECT THE DRUMS.  IN THE FRONT OF THE TRAILER THERE WAS A DRUM LEAKING FROM THE BOTTOM.  THE DRUM APPEARED TO BE A NEW DRUM AS I TURNED THE DRUM ON ITS SIDE I NOTICED A SMALL PINHOLE IN THE BOTTOM OF THE DRUM. THE HOLE HAD A SMALL AMOUNT OF RUST AROUND IT.  I TURNED THE DRUM SO THAT THE MATERIAL QUIT SEEPING OUT AND AS SOON AS I COULD, I PUT FLOOR DRY AROUND THE SPILL AND PUT THE DRUM IN A WASTE REPACK DRUM.  IN MY ESTIMATION ONLY ABOUT 5 GALLONS OR LESS WAS LOST OUT OF THIS DRUM.

column62: Defective Component or Device; Overfilled; Water Damage
column168: TANKER DRIVER PREPARED TO PUMP OIL INTO FRONT (2000 GALONS) COMPARTMENT OF OIL TANKER TRUCK.  THE DRIVER SWITCHED HIS VALVE TO CLOSE OFF HIS REAR COMPARTMENT (WHICH HELD OIL FROM PREVIOUS PICK UPS)  & OPENED HIS FRONT COMPARTMENT.  THE DRIVER THOUGHT HE SWITCHED THE VALVE, BUT IT DID NOT SWITCH TO THE FRONT COMPARTMENT.  AS HE STARTED PUNGING, THE REAR COMPARTMENT OVER FLOWED.  APPROXIMATELY 50 GALLONS OF OIL OVER FLOWED OUT IN THE PARKING LOT.  THE OIL WAS CLEANED UP WITH SORBENT SHEETS & 15 YARDS OF CONTAMINATED SOIL WAS EXCAVATED.  THIS AWAITING DISPOSAL INTO A LANDFILL.

column168: GASKET AT TOP BUNG CRIMPED, ALLOWING SMALL AMOUNT TO LEAK ON TOP OF TOTE.

column62: Defective Component or Device; Improper Preparation for Transportation
column168: AS THE DRIVER PARKED THE TRUCK TO VISIT HIS NEXT CUSTOMER ACCOUNT, HE OPENED THE REAR OF THE BOX TRUCK.  AT THAT TIME, HE DISCOVERED THE OVERTURNED CONTAINER, WITH ITS CONTENTS HAVING BEEN RELEASED BECAUSE ITS LID WAS KNOCKED OFF.  THE APPARENT CAUSE WAS THAT A PARTS WASHER MACHINE FELL FROM A SHELF ONTO THE CONTAINER, KNOCKING THE DRUM OVER AND THE LID OFF.  THE DRIVER CALLED "911" AND THE SPILL CLEAN-UP CONTRACTOR.  THE LOCAL FIRE DEPARTMENT RESPONDED, AND , AS A PRECAUTION, THE MAIN STREET WAS CLOSED TO VEHICULAR TRAFFIC AND TWO RETAIL ESTABLISHMENTS WERE EVACUATED.  THE CT DEPARTMENT OF ENVIRONMENTAL PROTECTION AUTHORIZED THE MOVING OF THE TRUCK TO A LESS CONGESTED AREA FOR COMPLETION OF THE CLEAN-UP.  NO CHEMICAL WAS RELEASED FROM THE REAR OF THE TRUCK.  TO PREVENT RECURRENCE, MACHINES WILL BE BETTER SECURED ON SHELVES AND THE DRIVER WAS RETRAINING ON SECURING THE LOAD.

column62: Derailment; Loose Closure, Component, or Device
column168: (A - D) AT APPROXIMATELY 1900 HOURS DECEMBER 14, 1995, CONRAIL TRAIN CNSE-3 TRAVELING EAST TO SELKIRK, NY WITH THREE LOCOMOTIVES, 82 LOADED AND 4 EMPTY CARS, DERAILED 51 CARS AT CP-184 (FONDA, NY).  THE 51 DERAILED CARS CONSISTED OF FREIGHT OF ALL KINDS INCLUDING 4 LOADED AND 1 RESIDUE HAZARDOUS MATERIAL TANK CARS.  AS A RESULT OF THE DERAILMENT SEVEN HOMES IN THE AREA WERE EVACUATED AS A PRECAUTIONARY MEASURE.  NO INJURIES WERE REPORTED AND THE EVACUEES WERE ALLOWED TO RETURN TO THEIR HOMES THE FOLLOWING MORNING WHEN THE AREA SURROUNDING THE ACCIDENT WAS DECLARED SAFE.  O H MATERIALS AND CLEAN HARBORS RESPONDED TO THE SCENE TO ASSIST IN THE TRANSFER AND CLEANUP OF THE HAZARDOUS MATERIALS.  ALSO, AS A RESULT OF THE DERAILMENT TANK CAR ACFX 87316, LOADED WITH SODIUM HYDROXIDE, SUSTAINED A 5 FT X 4 FT PUNCTURE IN THE B-END HEAD ALLOWING APPROXIMATELY 11,500 GALLONS OF PRODUCT TO ESCAPE FROM THE TANK CAR.  CLEAN HARBORS WAS ABLE TO TRANSFER THE REMAINING 4,500 GALLONS OF SODIUM HYDROXIDE IN TANK TRUCKS.  RESIDUE TANK CAR UTLX 14885, LAST CONTAINING FLUOROSILICIC ACID, SUSTAINED 4" X 4" HOLE IN THE BOTTOM OF THE TANK RESULTING IN APPROXIMATELY ONE GALLON OF SPILLAGE.  CLEAN HARBORS WAS ABLE TO TRANSFER 400 REMAINING GALLONS FROM THE TANK CAR.  TANK CARS DCTX 27424 AND ACFX 86273 LOADED WITH CHLORINE WERE RERAILED AND SET ON THE SIDING NEXT TO THE DERAILMENT SITE.  BOTH TANK CARS RECEIVED EXTENSIVE DAMAGE TO THE END SILLS, COUPLERS, RUNNING GEAR AND SAFETY APPLICANCES.  ADDITIONALLY, DURING HEAD OF TANK CAR DCTX 27424.  O H MATERIALS 10" X 1/2" X 7/16" DEEP WAS DISCOVERED AT THE 7' OCLOCK POSITION ON THE A-END HEAD OF TANK CAR DCTX 27424.   O H MATERIALS TRANSFERRED TANK DCTX 27424 INTO TANK CAR PROX 89492 ON 12/18/95.  TANK CAR ACFX 86273 WAS TRANSFERRED INTO TANK CAR PROX 82922 ON 12/19/95.  TANK CAR ACFX 94622, LOADED WITH HYDROCHLORIC ACID IS SCHEDULED TO BE TRANSFERRED INTO TANK TRUCKS 01/12/96.

column168: ON DECEMBER 27, 1995 AT 6:50PM AN UNSECURED DOME LID ON A TRAILER OPERATED BY RESOURCE TRANSPORTATION SERVICES ALLOWED APPROXIMATELY 20 GALLONS OF HAZARDOUS WASTE FUEL MIXTURE TO DRIP ONTO A CONCRETE ROADWAY INSIDE THE FACILITY; IN ADDITION A FEW DRIPS (LESS THAN 1 POUND) FELL ON A LIMESTONE ROAD ADJOINING THE CONCRETE ROAD.  THE HAZARDOUS FUEL MIXTURE CONTAINS MOSTLY OILS ALONG WITH SMALL AMOUNTS OF HAZARDOUS ORGANIC CONSTITUENTS (TYPICALLY METHYL ETHYL KETONE, METHANOL, TOLUENE, ETC).  THE SPILL WAS CONTAINED ON THE CONCRETE ROADWAY AND REMOVED USING ABSORB-ALL; VISIBLE CONTAMINATION WAS REMOVED FROM THE LIMESTONE ROAD USING SHOVELS. CONTAMINATED ABSORB-ALL AND LIMESTONE WAS DRUMMED FOR THERMAL DESTRUCTION OFFSITE AT A RCRA-PERMITTED INCINERATOR.

column168: AS THE DRUM WAS BEING UNLOADED, IT SLIPPED OFF THE DRUM DOLLY, PUNCTURING AN APPROX 2" HOLE, LEAKING APPROX 1/2 GAL.  THE SPILLED PRODUCT EVAPORATED IN THE TRAILER FLOOR BEFORE IT COULD BE CLEANED UP.  THE PUNCTURED DRUM WAS PLACED IN THE OS&D BAY FOR FURTHER DISPOSITION.  PREVIOUS MEETINGS HAVE BEEN HELD ON THE PROPER USE OF DRUM DOLLIES.

WE HAD A DOCK WORKER LOADING A SHORT SKID BEHIND THE DRUM OF H/M.  HE PUT ONE OF THE FORKBLADES THROUGH THE DRUM MAKING A 2" CUT IN DRUM.  TWO WORKERS GOT SOME CHEMICAL ON THERE CLOTHES AND HANDS.  THEY WERE SENT TO SEE THE DOCTOR AND SENT BACK TO WORK SAME DAY.  FERGUSON HARBOUR CLEANED UP THE SPILL.

A FORKLIFT WAS BACKING DOWN THE DOCK, WHICH WAS WET.  THE DRIVER ATTEMPTED TO STOP, COULD NOT, AND SLAMMED INTO THE WALL.  THE CANS WERE STACKED AGAINST THE WALL, AND WERE CRUSHED WHEN THE FORKLIFT STRUCK THEM.  THE DAMAGED CONTAINERS, ALONG WITH THE WASTE, WERE REOUPED IN A RECOVERY DRUM, AND PLACED IN THE OS&D BAY FOR FURTHER DISPOSITION.  THE DRIVER WAS GIVEN A LETTER OF INSTRUCTIONS, AND WE ALSO CONDUCTED A MEETING DETAILING FORKLIFT SAFETY.

column168: VENTING SYSTEM AT THE DESTINATION OF THIS SHIPMENT WAS NOT WORKING CORRECTLY - TANK PRESSURED UP AND FLOWED BACK RESULTING IN A SPILL OF 20 GALLONS OF DIESEL FUEL.  SPILL WAS CONTAINED AND CLEANED UP WITH MISSION PERSONNEL USING ON BOARD SPILL KIT.  STATIONS MANAGEMENT WAS NOTIFIED OF THE PROBLEM AND HAS CORRECTED IT.

YARD PERSONNEL OBSERVED TANK CAR ADMX 29341 SLOSHING LIQUID FROM THE MANWAY WHEN MOVED.  THE CAR WAS ISOLATED AND THE CSXT HAZMAT DEPARTMENT NOTIFIED.  THE CSXT HAZMAT MANAGER INSPECTED THE CAR AND FOUND THAT ONE OF THE EIGHT MANWAY BOLTS WAS LOOSE AND THAT THE MANWAY GASKET WAS BUNCHED UNDERNEATH THE LID LEAVING A GAP BETWEEN THE LID AND MANWAY NOZZLE.  AN ATTEMPT TO TIGHTEN THE MANWAY COVER WAS MADE TO NO AVAIL.  THE SHIPPER WAS CONTACTED AND INFORMED OF THE SITUATION.  THE SHIPPER ADVISED THAT THIS WAS A BONDED LOAD OF ALCOHOL AND THAT ANY REPAIR OR ALTERATION TO THE CAR MUST BE WITNESSED BY AUTHORIZED PERSONNEL.  ON 12/27/95, A REPRESENTATIVE OF THE CONSIGNEE WITNESSED THE REPLACEMENT OF THE MANWAY GASKET AND THE APPLICATION OF NEW CUSTODY SEALS.  THE CAR WAS THEN CHECKED FOR LEAKS AND FOUND TO BE OKAY FOR MOVEMENT.

column168: THIS SHIPMENT ARRIVED AT OUR TAMPA, FL TERMINAL WITHOUT ANY EVIDENCE OF LEAKAGE.  THERE WAS NO POOLING OF PRODUCT IN THE TRAILER OR ON THE DOCK. HOWEVER, UPON DELIVERY, THREE CARTONS WERE FOUND TO HAVE STAINS ON THE OUTSIDE.  TWO CARTONS WHICH HAD NO STAINS OR EVIDENCE OF ANY DAMAGE, WERE OPENED BY THE CONSIGNEE WITHOUT ANY DAMAGE FOUND.  HOWEVER, THE COMPLETE SHIPMENT WAS REFUSED DUE TO THE STAINS ON THE CARTONS.  CHEMTREC WAS NOT NOTIFIED SINCE THERE WAS NO EVIDENCE OF A LEAK OR SPILL.  THE SHIPMENT WAS RETURNED TO THE TERMINAL AND PLACED IN OS & D.  UPON FURTHER INVESTIGATION, IT WAS FOUND THAT ONE CARTON CONTAINED 3-JUGS WHICH HAD LOOSE CAPS AND HAD LEAKED PRODUCT ONTO THE OUTSIDE OF THAT CARTON AND ALSO ONTO TWO OTHER CARTONS WHICH WAS SITTING BENEATH THE CARTON THAT LEAKED. THE CAPS ON THE JUGS WERE TIGHTENED AND WERE ARE PRESENTLY AWAITING DISPOSITION FROM THE SHIPPER.  WE WILL CONTACT THE SHIPPER WITH REGARDS TO THE PROBLEM SO THEY CAN ADDRESS THE PACKAGING OF THIS MATERIAL.

column168: THE CARGO TANK TRUCK ARRIVED AT THE WASTEWATER TREATMENT PLANT TO MAKE A DELIVERY.  AFTER HOOK-UP, AIR PRESSURE WAS APPLIED TO THE TANK. column168: WHILE MAKING A PICK-UP AT VAN WATERS & ROGERS IN KINGSPORT, TN., IT WAS DISCOVERED THAT A 300 GALLON TOTE WAS LEAKING LIQUID INSIDE A DROMODARY BOX.  THE LIQUID WAS COMING FROM A CRACK IN THE TOTE.  THE SPILLED MATERIAL WAS CONTAINED INSIDE THE DROMODARY BOX ON A STEEL SECONDARY CONTAINMENT PAN.  FERGUSON HARBOR INC., OF GRAM, TN WAS CONTRACTED TO PERFORM CLEAN-UP AND REPAIR.  APPROXIMATELY 1 UP OF MATERIAL WAS RELEASED ONTO THE GROUND DURING CLEAN-UP.  THIS WAS PICKED UP BY THE CLEAN-UP CREW. THE TOTE WAS PATHED AND LOAD PROCEEDED ON TO DESTINATION WITH NO FURTHER PROBLEMS.

ONE METAL, 55 GALLON DRUM, FREE- STANDING ON A WOODEN PALLET WAS LOADED ONTO TRANSPORT UNIT (COMPANY IDENTIFICATION 28-1907) AT SEA-AIR HANDLING; 1900 146TH ST. ;SEATTLE, WA. AS PART OF A 11 PIECE SHIPMENT OF "FREIGHT ALL KINDS" AND 4 SHRINK-WRAPPED PALLETS CONTAINING MISC. NON HAZARDOUS FREIGHT ON 12-22-95.  THE METAL DRUM OF HAZARDOUS MATERIAL WAS POSITIONED AT THE REAR OF THE LOAD, ALONG THE LEFT WALL OF THE TRANSPORT UNIT AND WAS SECURED WITH A SINGLE LENGTH OF SISAL (3/8"DIA.) ROPE TIED DIAGONALLY RIGHT TO LEFT.  THE TRANSPORT UNIT WAS SEALED AND DISPATCHED, VIA LINE HAUL OPERATIONS TO FREMONT, CALIFORNIA VIA MEDFORD, OREGON.  ABOUT 35 MINUTES INTO THE RUN, HAVING TRAVELED APPROX. 26 MILES, AT 23:45 HOURS ON 12-22-95 THE LINE HAUL DRIVER NOTED IN HIS REAR VIEW MIRROR, A "SPRAY" COMING OFF THE LEFT SIDE OF TRANSPORT UNIT 28-1907.  WEATHER AND ROAD CONDITIONS COULD NOT ACCOUNT FOR THIS SPRAY, THE DRIVER PULLED HIS VEHICLE COMBINATION OVER ONTO THE SHOULDER OF INTERSTATE 5, SOUTHBOUND AT MILE-POST 127 TO INVESTIGATE.  LIQUID WAS COMING OUT OF THE REAR DOOR OF THE TRANSPORT UNIT (UNDERNEATH) BETWEEN THE DOOR SEAL FLOOR ONTO THE DIRT SHOULDER OF THE HIGHWAY.  A STRONG ODOR WAS ALSO NOTED AND A CALL FOR ASSISTANCE WAS MADE BY THE DRIVER VIA C.B. RADIO.  A WASHINGTON STATE PATROL OFFICER STOPPED AT THE SCENE TO SEE IF HELP WAS REQUIRED, AFTER PLACING THE DRIVER IN HIS PATROL VEHICLE AND MOVING BACK FROM THE TRUCK COMBINATION SOME 500 TO 600 FEET THE ODOR, AND FUMES FROM THE LIQUID BEGAN TO BOTHER BOTH THE DRIVER AND PATROLMAN WHO CALLED FOR ADDITIONAL HELP. AID UNITS FROM THE LAKEWOOD FIRE DEPT.  AND THE PIERCE COUNTY SHERIFF ARRIVED AT THE SITE AND RENDERED ASSISTANCE.  THE PATROL OFFICER AND THE DRIVER WERE TAKEN TO THE HOSPITAL BY AID CAR FOR TREATMENT.  THE IMMEDIATE AREA WEST OF THE SITE WAS EVACUATED, THIS CONSISTED OF A SMALL APARTMENT A VEHICLE MAINTENANCE SHOP AND POSSIBLY A SMALL STORE.  ADDITIONAL WASHINGTON STATE POLICE AND WASHINGTON DEPARTMENT OF ECOLOGY- SPILL RESPONSE ARRIVED ALONG WITH PERSONNEL FROM TNT REDDAWAY TRUCK LINE, NEXT CAME A TEAM FROM MCCORD AIRFORCE BASE-HAZARDOUS RESPONSE UNIT ALONG WITH A CREW FROM OLYMPUS ENVIRONMENTAL INC., KENT, WA. TO HANDLE CONTAINMENT, CLEAN-UP AND REMEDIATE THE SITE.  EMERGENCY RESPONSE INFORMATION WAS SECURED, AND THE UNIT WAS OPENED.  THE 55 GALLON DRUM WAS LAYING ON ITS SIDE, WITH THE BOTTOM OF THE DRUM ON THE WOODEN PALLET AND THE TOP RESTING ON THE TRAILER FLOOR, THE ROPE USED TO SECURE THE DRUM WAS LOOSE AND LAYING ACROSS THE WOODEN PALLET.  THE DRUM CONTAINING THE HAZARDOUS MATERIAL WAS EMPTY, AND WAS PUT INTO A RECCOVERY DRUM ALONG WITH THE ABSORBENT MATERIAL AND SOME DIRT FROM THE HIGHWAY THAT WAS REMOVED, THE SITE WAS CLEANED AND INSPECTED.  THE RECOVERY DRUM WAS LABELED AND LOADED ONTO THE TRAILER, SECURED AND RELEASED FOR TRANSPORT TO THE TNT REDDAWAY TRUCK LINE TERMINAL IN CLACKAMAS, OREGON.  THE TRAILER AND ALL ITS CONTENTS WERE IMPOUNDED ON ARRIVAL AT THE CLACKAMAS, OREGON LOCA
NO REMARKS

column168: COMBINATION UNIT ARRIVED AT UNLOAD SITE AND BEGAN UNLOADING PROCESS. HATCHES AND VALVES WERE OPEN AND PRODUCT FLOWED INTO COLLECTION PIT.  WHEN FLOW FROM TRAILER STOPPED, DRIVER BELIEVED THAT TANK WAS EMPTY.  UNLOADING VALVE WAS CLOSED AN DOT TANK HATCH WAS LEFT CRACKED OPEN TO ALLOW FOR HEAT CONTRACTION.  AS UNIT NEARED EXIT GATE TO PLANT, DRIVER STOPPED TO ADJUST MIRROR.  AFTER ADJUSTMENT WAS MADE DRIVER STARTED OUT AGAIN AND FELT "TUG" IN REAR TRAILER AND THOUGHT REAR BRAKE HAD FAILED TO RELEASE. DRIVER STOPPED, APPLIED AND RELEASED BRAKE THEN PULLED OUT AGAIN NOT DETECTING "TUG".   VEHICLE EXITED GATE AND MADE LEFT TURN ONTO HIGHWAY 430.  ON COMPLETION OF TURN DRIVER LOOKED BACK AND SAW THAT PRODUCT HAD SLOSHED OUT OF THE HATCH AND ONTO THE ROADWAY.  DRIVER STOPPED, CLOSED HATCH AND TURNED UNIT AROUND, RE-ENTERED PLANT AND UNLOADED REMAINING PRODUCT. FUTURE PROCEDURES WILL INSIST ON VISUAL VERIFICATION OF AN EMPTY TANK.

A VACUUM TRAILER WAS DISPATCHED TO KING INDUSTRIES, INC. LOCATED AT SCIENCE ROAD IN FAIRFIELD, CT. IN ORDER TO LOAD AND TRANSPORT A SHIPMENT OF HAZARDOUS WASTE FOR OFF-SITE DISPOSAL. UPON ARRIVAL AT KING INDUSTRIES, THE DRIVER OF THE VACUUM TRAILER INITIATED THE STEPS NECESSARY TO BEGIN LOADING HIS VEHICLE. ONE STEP IN THE PROCEDURE INVOLVES OPENING THE DRAIN VALVES ON THE VEHICLE'S SCRUBBER SYSTEM AND VACUUM PUMP ASSEMBLIES TO DRAIN ANY RESIDUAL MATERIAL THAT COULD HAVE COLLECTED IN THESE SYSTEMS FROM A PREVIOUS SHIPMENT. THE DRIVER PERFORMED THIS STEP AND CLOSED THE DRAIN VALVES AFTER IT WAS DETERMINED THAT THE SYSTEMS CONTAINED NO RESIDUAL LIQUID. ONCE THE SETUP AND INSPECTION OF THE VEHICLE WAS COMPLETE, THE DRIVER ENGAGED THE VACUUM PUMP IN ORDER TO INITIATE LOADING THE VEHICLE. IT WAS AT THIS POINT THAT APPROXIMATELY 2 GALLONS OF MATERIAL ESCAPED FROM THE SCRUBBER SYSTEMS VENT STACK ONTO THE SIDE OF THE VEHICLE THE SURROUNDING PARKING AREA AND A SNOW BANK. IN ADDITION, AN EMPLOYEE OF KING INDUSTRIES AND HIS HOME DISPATCHER OF THE INCIDENT. FACILITY PERSONNEL IMMEDIATELY ABSORBED ALL FREE LIQUIDS WITH SPEEDY DRI, COLLECTED THE CONTAMINATED SNOW AND DECONTAMINATED THE SIDE OF THE VEHICLE. ALL CLEAN-UP DEBRIS AND CONTAMINATED SNOW WAS CONTAINERIZED AND PLACED INTO STORAGE PENDING OFF-SITE DISPOSAL AT A FULLY LICENSED WASTE MANAGEMENT FACILITY. A REVIEW OF THE INCIDENT INDICATED THAT THE PROBABLE CAUSE OF THE RELEASE CAN BE ATTRIBUTED TO MATERIAL FROM THE PREVIOUS LOAD FREEZING IN THE PIPE WORK OF THE SCRUBBER AND VACUUM SYSTEM. FURTHERMORE, IT IS BELIEVE THAT WHEN THE VACUUM UNIT WAS ENGAGED, THE PRESSURE CREATED BY THIS SYSTEM DISLODGED AN ICE PLUG WHICH, IN TURN, ALLOWED RESIDUAL LIQUID BEHIND THE ICE PLUG TO ESCAPE FROM THE VENT STACK. PLEASE NOTE THAT THE FORMATION OF THE ICE PLUG PREVENTED THE DRIVER FROM DISCOVERING THE RESIDUAL LIQUID IN THE SCRUBBER UNIT WHEN HE OPENED THE DRAIN VALVES PRIOR TO INITIATING THE LOADING PROCEDURES. IN ORDER TO PREVENT A RECURRENCE OF THIS EVENT, DRIVERS AND LOADING PERSONNEL HAVE BEEN RE-INSTRUCTED TO INSURE THAT ALL SCRUBBER UNITS ARE DRAINED COMPLETELY PRIOR TO SUBSEQUENT DISPATCH.

SPECIAL AGENT HAZARDOUS MATERIALS, VERN LIBBY, WAS NOTIFIED BY MIKE KAMBARN, UPMF, SEATTLE, WA. ADVISING CONTAINER HCLU 456248, WAS NOTED TO BE LEAKING AND HAD BEEN PLACED ON RAMP 6.  IN ADDITION LIBBY RECEIVED A PAGE FROM FLETCHER JAMISON, SYO, SEATTLE, ADVISING HE HAD ADVISED THE TWO SWITCHING CREWS WORKING AND THE CREW HAULER TO EVACUATE TO THE CORNER OF 4TH AVE. S. AND S. DAWSON ST.  INSPECTION OF CONTAINER HLCU 456248 DEVELOPED THE FOLLOWING;  CONTAINER HLCU 456248 HAD JUST ARRIVED IN TRAIN GSSED 29 AND WAS LOCATED IN RAMP TRACK 6.  THE CONTAINER WAS LOADED ON FLATCAR PC522716.  THE CONTAINER APPEARED TO BE LEAKING THROUGH THE FLOOR NEAR THE REAR OF THE CONTAINER.  A SMALL QUANTITY OF LIQUID WAS NOTED ON THE DECK OF THE FLATCAR.  THE CONTAINER WAS OFF LOADED FOR INSPECTION. THE RIGHT REAR DOOR WAS OPEN NOTING 3 LOOSE PALLET BOARDS AS A FEEBLE ATTEMPT TO BLOCK AND BRACE THE LOAD.  IT WAS NOTED THAT THE CARGO (COMPRESSED GAS CYLINDERS) BEHIND THE CRUSHED DRUMS IN THE DOOR WAY HAD NOT BEEN PROPERLY SECURED AND HAD FALLEN OVER ONTO THE METAL DRUMS RESULTING IN 22 OF 32 25 LITER METAL DRUMS LEAKING.  THE CONTAINER DOOR WAS CLOSED, CONTAINER RELOADED ONTO THE FLATCAR ISOLATED AND CREWS RETURNED TO WORK.  PLEASE BE ADVISED THERE WERE A NUMBER OF DISCREPANCIES AND BILLING ERRORS THEY WERE DEVELOPED INVOLVING CONTAINER HLCU 456248 DEVELOPED AS FOLLOWS:  LIBBY WAS UNABLE TO CONTACT THE SHIPPER OR LOCAL CONSIGNEE ACCOUNT 24 HOUR EMERGENCY TELEPHONE CONTACT NUMBER LISTED ON THE WAYBILL WAS FOR CHEMTREC. 1-800-424-9300.  THE LISTED SHIPPER AND CONSIGNEE ON CR WB 127128 11 22 HAPAG LLOYD AMERICA DOES NOT SUBSCRIBE TO CHEMTREC FOR THEIR SERVICES. THE WAYBILL INDICATED THERE WERE ONLY 4 CYLINDERS OF COMPRESSED NON FLAMMABLE GAS.  HOWEVER THERE WERE TOTAL OF 60 CYLINDERS OF NON FLAMMABLE GAS (ORDINARY AIR)  LOADED IN THE CONTAINER IN QUESTION.  ALSO NOTED 200 LITERS OF ALKALINITY CONTROL, CORROSIVE 8 LOADED IN THE CONTAINER. HOWEVER NOT LISTED ON THE WAYBILL IN THE SHIPPING DESCRIPTION.  TO EXPEDITE THE CLEANUP LIBBY CONTRACTED WITH FOSS ENVIRONMENTAL SEATTLE TO CLEAN THE FLATCAR, CONTAIN, RECOVER AND DISPOSE OF ANY WASTE GENERATED FROM CONTAINER HLCU 456248.  HOWEVER, AT A LATER DATE LIBBY WAS ABLE TO CONTACT DAVID FARRELL, SUPERVISOR UNITOR SHIPS SERVICE, BURNBY, B.C. CANADA WHO ACKNOWLEDGED RESPONSIBILITY AND ACCEPTED ALL CHARGES RELATED TTHIS INCIDENT ON BEHALF OF UNITOR SHIPS SERVICE.

column168: DRIVER WAS DISPACHED 1112 W LAFAYETTE AVE. AS BEING OUT OF OIL. column62: Improper Preparation for Transportation; Water Damage
column168: DEAN C. COOPER, MANAGER, CHEMICAL TRANSPORTATION SAFETY, WAS NOTIFIED BY JEFF BROWN, OPERATIONS MANAGER, IN-TERMINAL SERVICES, UNION PACIFIC RAILROAD, INTERMODAL FACILITY, LOS ANGELES, CALIFORNIA, THAT A TRAILER WAS NOTED LEAKING UPON ARRIVAL THAT THE RAMP.  THE TRAILER WAS ON THE WEST BOUND CHLAZ-04 AND OBSERVED LEAKING NEAR THE REAR DOORS WHILE IT WAS BEING DERAMPED FROM THE TRAIN BY THE CRANE OPERATOR.  THE TRAILER WAS MOVED TO DIRT LOT #16 AND ISOLATED PENDING INSPECTION.  AS MANAGER COOPER WAS NOT AVAILABLE TO RESPOND, CONTACT WAS MADE WITH ENVIRONMENTAL TRANSLOADING SERVICES, AND REQUESTED THEY RESPOND, EVALUATE, AND REMEDIATE THE LEAKING MATERIAL.  UPON INSPECTION OF THE TRAILER, DEVELOP THERE WERE (4) EACH 55 GALLON DRUMS AGAINST THE REAR DOORS.  ONE OF THE DRUMS WAS AN EMPTY THAT HAD BEEN PLACED IN THE TRAILER TO FILL A VOID SPACE.  THE TRAILER WAS 102 INCHES WIDE, AND THE DRUMS WERE NOT BLOCKED AND BRACED TO COMPENSATE FOR THE ADDITIONAL WIDTH OF THE TRAILER.  THERE WERE (4) USED PALLETS DIRECTLY BEHIND THE ROW OF DRUMS, SEPARATING THEM FROM SEVERAL OTHER ROWS OF DRUMS CONTAINING THE SAME COMMODITY.  THE EXISTING BLOCKING AND BRACING IS NOT APPROVED PER BOE 6C FOR TRANSPORTATION OF HAZARDOUS COMMODITIES.  ONE DRUM ON THE LEFT SIDE OF THE TRAILER IN THE FIRST ROW, HAD ROTATED IN PLACED DURING TRANSIT, AS THERE WAS NO BLOCKING AND BRACING TO PREVENT MOVEMENT. THE DRUM ROTATED IN PLACE AGAINST THE EMPTY FILLER DRUM, AND IN THE PROCESS OF ROTATING, THE BOTTOM CHIME WORE A GROVE IN THE WOOD FLOORING. A PORTION OF THE DRUM WAS ALSO RUBBING AGAINST THE METAL TO METAL CONTACT EVENTUALLY WORE THROUGH THE BOTTOM CHIME OF THE DRUM, RELEASING THE ENTIRE CONENTS.  THE FLOOR WAS DECONED AND THE EXISTING FREIGHT PLACED BACK INTO THE ORIGINAL TRAILER FOR DELIVERY TO THE CONSIGNEE.  THE DAMAGED DRUM WAS OVERPACKED AND ALSO PLACED BACK INTO THE TRAILER AT THE REQUEST OF THE CONSIGNEE.  DUE TO THE TYPE OF COMMODITY AND LIMITED QUANTITY RELEASED, THERE WERE NO NOTIFICATIONS MADE TO THE REGULATORY AGENCIES.

column62: Impact with Sharp or Protruding Object (e.g., nails)
column168: DEAN C. COOPER, MANAGER, CHEMICAL TRANSPORTATION SAFETY, WAS NOTIFIED BY JEFF BROWN, OPERATIONS MANAGER, IN-TERMINAL SERVICES, UNION PACIFIC RAILROAD, INTERMODAL FACILITY, LOS ANGELES, CALIFORNIA, WHO ADVISED AN OUTSIDE DRIVER HAD ATTEMPTED TO PICK UP A CONTAINER FOR DELIVERY WHEN HE OBSERVED A LIQUID LEAKING THROUGH THE FLOOR.  MANAGER BROWN HAD THE CONTAINER MOVED FROM TRAILER STORAGE LOT W-1, TO DIRT LOT #16, AND ISOLATED PENDING INSPECTION.  MANAGER COOPER DROVE TO THE INTERMODAL FACILITY AND NOTED THE CONTAINER IMPROPERLY PLACARDED, WITH ALL FOUR PLACARDS PLACED SQUARE, RATHER THAN ON DIAMOND POINT, IN VIOLATION OF 49 CFR, SECTION 172.516 (C) (5).  THERE WAS A SMALL AMOUNT OF PRODUCT DRIPPING FROM THE UNDERCARRIAGE NEAR THE CENTER OF THE CONTAINER.  THE LIQUID WAS TESTED FOR PH AND HAD A READING IN THE LOW ACIDIC RANGE.  THE REAR DOOR SEAL, BECKART 942, WAS REMOVED TO OPEN THE DOORS IN ORDER TO INSPECT THE LADING.  (6) TOTE'S, CONTAINING 275 GALLONS OF POLYAL 201, A CORROSIVE LIQUID, WERE ACROSS THE REAR OF THE CONTAINER, 4 FEET IN FROM THE DOORWAY.  (2) 2X4'S NAILED SIDE WALL TO SIDE WALL ON THE FLOORING, ALONG WITH SEVERAL SMALL PIECES OF 2X4 NAILED TO THE FLOORING BETWEEN THE TOTE'S, HAVE BEEN ADEQUATE FOR FAK LADING, IT DOES NOT MEET THE REQUIREMENTS PER BOE 6C BLOCKING AND BRACING REQUIREMENTS FOR THE TRANSPORTATION OF HAZARDOUS MATERIALS.  DIRECTLY BEHIND THE TOTE'S WERE POLY 55 GALLON DRUMS LOADED IN A 4-3-4 PATTERN.  THERE WAS NO SEPARATION BETWEEN THE TOTES AND THE DRUMS.  DUE TO THE WAY THE CONTAINER WAS LOADED, ENTRY HAD TO BE MADE OVER THE TOPS OF THE DRUMS IN AN EFFORT TO LOCATE THE LEAKING PRODUCT.  THE AREA OF THE LEAK WAS LOCATED, HOWEVER, THE SPECIFIC LEAKING DRUM COULD NOT BE LOCATED WITHOUT REMOVING THE LADING AND INSPECTING EACH INDIVIDUAL CONTAINER.  MANAGER COOPER CONTACTED K LINE, MURRAY HILL, NEW JERSEY, AND WAS ADVISED THE BILLING WAS INITIATED BY RAIL BRIDGE, MURRAY HILL, NEW JERSEY.  RAIL BRIDGE WAS ONLY A THIRD PARTY SHIPPER AND REFERRED THE CONTACT TO ALL MODES, INC., PARK CITY, ILLINOIS, WHO IS A SHIPPERS AGENT.  ALL MODES JUST HANDLES THE PAPERWORK FOR THE ACTUAL SHIPPER, WHO LOADED THIS CONTAINER AT THEIR FACILITY, BECKHARDT ENVIRONMENTAL. column168: 02:47 SORT SUPERVISOR MIKE BALLEIN REPORTED A SHIPMENT EMITTING AN ODOR OF GASOLINE, 2 EMPLOYEES IN CONTACT, TO HAZ MAT DISPATCH.  THE SHIPMENT WAS LOCATED OUTSIDE GASOLINE, 2 EMPLOYEES IN CONTACT, TO HAZMAT DISPATCH.  THE SHIPMENT WAS LOCATED OUTSIDE DOOR-A 13 OF OUR SORT FACILITY LOCATED AT ABX AIR INC, 145 HUNTER DRIVE, WILMINGTON OHIO 45177.  P/T HAZ MAT SPILL TECHNICIAN JEFF MCLAUGHLIN IN RESPONDED UPON ARRIVAL, HE OBSERVED A BLUE PLASTIC RECEPTACLE UPSIDE DOWN.  TEHNICIAN MCLAUGHLIN DONNED AN ORGANIC VAPOR CARTRIDGE RESPIRATOR TO INVESTIGATE THE INNER CONTENTS OF THE PLASTIC RECEPTACLE.  INSIDE THE PLASTIC RECEPTACLE WAS AN ENGINE.  THIS HAD LEAKED APPROX. 4 TO 6 OUNCES OF GASOLINE.  THIS WAS SOME FUEL THAT WAS LEFT IN THE ENGINE THAT LEAKED INSIDE THE PLASTIC RECEPTACLE THAT CAUSED THE ODOR.  THIS SHIPMENT WAS NOT PROPERLY MARKED, LABELED AND PROPER CERTIFICATION DID NOT ACCOMPANY THIS SHIPMENT TO INDICATE THAT ITS CONTENTS WERE REGULATED AS HAZARDOUS MATERIALS.  THIS SHIPMENT IS AT THE HAZMAT SORT IN THE SECURITY CAGE, UNDER LOCK AND KEY, PENDING INVESTIGATION BY THE FAA.

IT WAS IMPOSSIBLE TO TELL HOW MANY OF THE BOTTLES ACTUALLY LOST PRODUCT, SEVERAL HAD LOOSE CAPS, NONE OF THE BOTTLES ACTUALLY LOST PRODUCT, SEVERAL HAD LOOSE CAPS, NONE OF THE BOTTLES WERE DAMAGED, APPROXIMATELY 16 OZ TOTAL LEAKED.  THE LABELS ON THE PLASTIC BOTTLES READ THAT THE MATERIAL IS FLAMMABLE.  THIS SHIPMENT IS CURRENTLY BEING HELD IN OUR HAZMAT SECURITY CAGE UNDER LOCK  AND KEY PENDING RELEASE BY THE FAA. column168: A WHEEL CHAIR WAS LOADED IN SEATTLE AND DUE TO THE HEIGHT OF THE CHAIR WAS LEFT LAYING ON IT'S SIDE IN THE AIRCRAFT BIN.  THE PASSENGER HAD ASSURED STATION PERSONNEL THAT THE BATTERY WAS A NON-SPILLABLE TYPE.  THE CABLES TO THE BATTERY WERE DISCONNECTED AND INSULATED TO PREVENT POSSIBLE SHORT-CIRCUIT WHICH IS ACCEPTABLE FOR A NON-SPILLABLE BATTERY.  THE ACCEPTING PERSONNEL SHOULD HAVE VISUALLY INSPECTED THE BATTERY TO DETERMINE THE TYPE OF BATTERY IN THE WHEEL CHAIR.  BATTERY FLUID LEAKED THOUGH THE CAP COVERS ON THE BATTERY INTO THE AIRCRAFT BIN .  AT L A X WHERE THE SPILL WAS DISCOVERED WE EXPERIENCED AN HOUR DELAY ON THE AIRCRAFT WHILE THE BIN WAS CLEANED AND INSPECTED BY A MECHANIC.  BOTH ACCEPTING AGENTS IN SEA HAVE BEEN DISCIPLINED FOR FAILING TO FOLLOW

1 DRUM OF PRINTING INK WAS PUNCTURED BY A FORKLIFT WHILE BEING UNLOADED. THE SPLILL WAS CONTAINED TO THE PACKAGE.  THE ENVIORNMENTAL AFFAIRS DEPT. WAS CONTACTED FOR DISPOSAL OF THE PACKAGE.  MARK ESTRADA

column168: ON 122195 AT APPROXIMATELY 3PM, MANAGER CHEMICAL TRANSPORTATION SAFETY GEOFFREY REEDER, WAS NOTIFIED OF A LEAKING TANK CAR AT SETTEGAST YARD. THE CAR CONTAINED ANHYDROUS AMMONIA.  REEDER RESPONDED AND FOUND THE CAR LEAKING FROM THE SAFETY RELIEF VALVE.  REEDER REMOVED SEAL CF IND 058704 AND OPENED THE PROTECTIVE HOUSING COVER.  THE PLUG COULD NOT BE REMOVED FROM THE SAMPLE VALVE TO CHECK THE PRESSURE.  THE PRESSURE WAS CHECKED USING THE GAUGING DEVICE AND FOUND TO BE 50 PSI.  THE GAUGING DEVICE WAS STUCK SO THE OUTAGE COULD NOT BE READ.  REEDER DETERMINED THE O-RINGS IN THE MIDLAND TYPE A 1229 SAFETY RELIEF VALVE WERE DEFECTIVE.  REGIONAL MANAGER TOM ROBINSON AND SENIOR MANAGER BOB STINE RESPONDED TO CHANGE THE O-RINGS.  ONCE THE CAP WAS REMOVED STINE FOUND THE O-RINGS WERE BRITTLE AND CRACKED.  THERE WAS ALSO A THIRD "RING" MADE OF AN UNKNOWN MATERIAL. THIS RING WAS AT THE EDGE OF THE CAP AND SHOULD NOT HAVE BEEN INPLACE. NEW O-RINGS WERE INSTALLED AND THE CAP REPLACED.  THIS STOPPED THE LEAK. THE CAR WAS RELEASED FOR MOVEMENT.  THE SHIPPER AND CHEMTREC WERE NOTIFIED.  A TAG ON THE VALVE INDICATED IT WAS SERVICED ON 08-31-94 BY GLENCO MFG.

column168: ON DECEMBER 19, 1995 AT APPROXIMATELY 11:45 a.m. DRIVER, ROGER HELDT, WAS MADE AWARE BY OTHER TRUCK DRIVERS THAT PRODUCT FROM HIS TRUCK WAS SPRAYING OTHER TRUCKS ON THE HIGHWAY.  DRIVER PROCEEDED TO THE NEXT TRUCK STOP, THE STANDARD TRUCK STOP AT WOODHULL, IL, I-74, EXIT 32, THERE HE CONTACTED Q CARRIER'S SAFETY DEPARTMENT, THE STATE PATROL, AND CHEMTREC.  DRIVER SECURED AREA.  THE SAFETY DEPARTMENT CONTACTED THE SHIPPER, PARA-CHEM SOUTHERN, INC.  OF SIMPSONVILLE, SC.  AFTER 25 MINUTES ON "HOLD", DOUG WARD REFERREDUS TO B.L. EUDY, ALSO WITH PARA-CHEM, WHO WAS UNAVAILABLE. LEFT MESSAGE FOR MR. EUDY.  DRIVERS FROM LANDSTAR, UNITED VAN LINES, AND WERNER ENTERPRISE CALLED Q CARRIERS TO REPORT DAMAGE TO THEIR TRUCK BY THE PRODUCT.  INCIDENT MAY INVOLVE FIVE TRUCKS.  DRIVERS WERE INSTRUCTED TO WORK WITH OUT INSURANCE COMPANY, EMPIRE FIRE AND MARINE INSURANCES COMPANY.  IN CONVERSATION WITH TROOPER HINES, AND TWO "Q" SAFETY DEPARTMENT STAFF MEMBERS, "Q" EXPRESSED DESIRE TO DO EVERYTHING POSSIBLE TO REMEDY THIS SPILL.  "Q" AUTHORIZED TROOPER HINES AND "Q" DRIVER TO TAKE ANY NECESSARY MEASURES IMMEDIATELY.  TROOPER HINES DISCOVERED THAT THE PRODUCT ONE THE TRAILER WAS INCORRECTLY LISTED ON THE BILL OF LADING. PARA-CHEM FAXES A CORRECTED BILL OF LADING. PARA-CHEM FAXED MSDS TO Q CARRIERS, MN. Q CARRIERS FAXED MSDS TO DRIVER AND TROPPER HINES IN IL. DRIVER SPOKE TO MR. EUDY, OF SHIPPER PARA-CHEM IN CONFERENCE CALL WITH CHEMTREC.  MR. EUDY RETURNED CAPP TO "Q" SAFETY DEPARTMENT SPENT AN EXTENDED PERIOD OF TIME PHONING CLEAN-UP ORGANIZARION.  ALL THE COMPANIES CONTACTED WERE ALREADY ON OTHER SITES, AND WERE UNABLE TO COMMIT TO US. EACH REFERRED US TO OTHER COMPANIES.  TROOPER HINES AND "Q" DRIVER ORDERED A BACK-HOE (HLR CARLSON CONSTUCTION, INC.) TO DIG A TRECH AROUND THE TRAILER TO CONTAIN LEAKING PRODUCT.  MR. EUDY (OF SHIPPER PARA-CHEM) CALLED "Q" SAFETY DEPARTMENT TO SAY HE WAS UNSUCCESSFUL IN FINDING CLEAN-UP COMPANY.  LEFT RESPONSIBILITY TO "Q"/  AT ABOUT 2:00P.M. "Q" STAFF FOUND TWO ORGANIZATION THAT COULD HELP US.  WE CONTACTED WITH EMERGENCY MANAGEMENT SERVICE, INC. (EMS) OF OSCO, IL.  EMS ARRIVED AT THE SITE ABOUT 3:15p.m. TO PREPARE FOR CLEAN-UP.  EMS SECURED THE AREA AND ENTERED THE TRAILER TO DETERMINE SCOPE OF CLEAN-UP.  WORK BY EMS CONTINUED ON CLEAN-UP AND TRANSFER OF LOAD TO ANOTHER TRAILER.  EMS WORKED 12/19, 12/20, 12/21, 12/26, 12/28.  DUE TO FROZEN GROUND, CLEAN-UP WAS SLOW.  AS OF 1/15/96, THE CONTAMINATED SOIL IS EXCAVATED, AND ISOLATED IN A CONTAINER, WAITING FOR PROCESSING OF SOIL SAMPLES.  EMS CONTINUES TO WORK ON THE PROJECT, AND ANTICIPATED COMPLETION OF DISPOSAL BY EARLY FEBRUARY.

column42: GASOLINE INCLUDES GASOLINE MIXED WITH ETHYL ALCOHOL, WITH NOT MORE THAN 10% ALCOHOL
column168: AS THE SAFETY ASSISTANT FOR BENETO TANK LINES, I WAS NOTIFIED OF THE SPILL AT MY HOME IN SACRAMENTO AT 11:20am BY OUR DISPATCH OFFICE LOCATED IN WEST SACRAMENTO.  I IMMEDIATELY CONTACTED OUR DRIVER AND CAPTAIN JAY HANSON OF THE DALY CITY FIRE DEPARTMENT AT THE SCENE OF THE INCIDENT.  AT THIS POINT, OUR DRIVER, JIM LYNCH, INFORMED ME OF WHAT HAPPENED AND CAPTAIN HANSON TOLD ME THAT THE FIRE DEPARTMENT WAS WASHING THE GASOLINE THROUGH THE STORM DRAIN SYSTEM AND WOULD PROBABLY CONTINUE TO SO SO FOR ANOTHER HOUR OR SO.  PRIOR TO LEAVING MY HOME FOR THE OFFICE. I PHONED THE OWNER OF THE COMPANY AND DISCUSSED WITH HIM WHAT THE NEXT COURSE OF ACTION WOULD BE.  UPON ARRIVING AT OUR WEST SACRAMENTO OFFICE, I NOTIFIED THE NATIONAL RESPONSE CENTER AND DISPATCHED FIVE DENETO EMERGENCY RESPONSE VEHICLES INCLUDING TWO EMERGENCY RESPONSE TRAILERS EQUIPPED WITH AUTHORIZED CONTAINERS, ABSORBANT MATERIAL, BOOMS, ETC. TO THE SCENE.  AFTER TALKING TO WILLIAM LENT, THE SAN MATEO COUNTY HAZARDOUS MATERIALS PROGRAM MANAGER, I ALSO REQUESTED A VACUUM TRUCK, EMERGENCY RESPONSE TRUCK AND A HAZARDOS MATERIAL CREW FROM INTERNATIONAL TECHNOLOGY CORPORATION (IT) BE DISPATCHED TO THE SCENE TO PROVIDE ANY ADDITIONAL ASSISTANCE THAT MAY BE REQUIRED. PRIOR TO LEAVING OUT WEST SACRAMENTO OFFICE TO INVESTIGATE THE INCIDENT, I LEFT ALL OF MY NOTES REGARDING THE STATUS OF THE SPILL WITH BENTO TANK LINES SAFETY DIRECTOR, BOB MARCH.  UPON ARRIVING AT THE STATION AT APPROXIMATELY 4:30pm, I PARKED MY 1987 4x4 FORD BRONCO THEN IMMEDIATELY DECIDED TO MOVE IT TO ANOTHER LOCATION.  WHEN I PUT THE TRUCK IN REVERSE, I COULD NOT BACK UP AS THE REAR TIRES WRE SPINNING DUE TO THE WET PAVEMENT AND STEEP INCLINE OF THE STATION'S PARKING LOT AT IT'S NORTH ENTRANCE-EXACTLY WHERE OUR TRUCK HAD SKIDDED OUT SEVERAL HOURS EARLIER! THE SHOP SUPERVISOR FROM OUR MARTINEZ TERMINAL INFORMED ME THAT HE HAD COMPLETED AN INSPECTION AND TEST OF THE BRAKES ON THE TRUCK AT THE SCENE AND THEY APPEARED TO BE WORKING NORMAL.  FURTHER INVESTIGATION REVEALED THERE WAS NO DAMAGE TO OUR EQUIPMENT, THE STATION, OR ROAD THE TRUCK SKIDDED ACROSS BEFORE OUT DRIVER WAS ABLE TO JUMP INTO THE CAB AND BRING THE UNIT TO A STOP.
column172: Tank truck, tank mounted on truck chassis

column168: ADRIAN YATES NOTIFIED SUPERVISOR, SCOTT HOPPER, WHO THEN NOTIFIED FIRST RESPONDER RICK PARSLOW OF CORROSIVE LIQUID LEAKING PACKAGE IN TRL. XTRZ22169.  THE DECISION TREE WAS REFERRED TO, USING THE PROPER PPE THE PACKAGE WAS BROUGHT TO THE DMP AREA TO BE PROCESSED BY FIRST RESPONDERS, BRETT REEDER AND RICK PARSLOW.  AFTER GETTING AN INITIAL PH READING OF 12 BRETT AND RICK NEUTRALIZED THE SPILL USING SODIUM BICARBONATE UNTIL A READING OF 7 WAS ATTAINED.  USING PROPER PPE (APRON, GLOVES, BOOTS, AND SCBA)  THE PACKAGE WAS PROCESSED THROUGH THE DMP PROGRAM.  SPILL CARDBOARD BOX AND TRAILER FLOOR.

PACKAGE WAS FOUND LEAKING BY A RE-LOADER ON PD-5.  FOLLOWED 12 HOUR RESPONSE PROCESS.  DAWNED FULL PPE, FOLLOWED DECISION TREE, FOLLOWED FLAMMABLE LIQUID RESPONSE SHEET, AND PROCESSED ACCORDINGLY TO DMP PROCEDURES.

LOOSE CAP ON BOTTLE OF CLEANER CONTAINING ISOPROPLY ALCOHOL.  SATURATED THE CARDBOARD.  REPORTED TO THE AREA WITH SPILLCART.  DONNED MY GOGGLES, GLOVES, APRON, AND BOOTS.  USED THE LEAKING PACKING DECISION TREE AND DETERMINED THAT I NEED THE FLAMMABLE LIQUID RESPONSE SHEETS.  NO LIQUID SPILLED-ONLY CARDBOARD SATURATED.  DISCOVERED THAT THE CAP WAS NOT ON THE WHOLE WAY.  REPLACED CAP PROPERLY - PUT FOUR 1 GALLON BOTTLES IN A NEW BOX.  DISPOSED OF THE SATURATED CARDBOARD VIA DAMAGE MATERIAL PROCEDURE. SHIPPER WAS NOTIFIED THAT THE BOTTLE CAP WAS NOT SCREWED ON CORRECTLY.

LINDA HAYES WENT TO MEET DRIVER RICH AMOS TRUCK #15820, AT 5528 PRINCESS ANNE ROAD, VIRGINIA BEACH, VIRGINIA 23462 WITH NEW TRUCK!  UNLOADED ALLUM CONTAINATED PACKAGES TO NEW TRUCK.  RETURNING TO BUILDING WITH 5 CONTAINATED PACKAGES & TRUCK #15820.  DECISION TREE REFERRED US TO CORROSIVE RESPONSE GUIDE, STILL IN 5 CBA GEAR WE CLEANED AND DECONTAMINATED TRUCK, REWRAPING 4 PACKAGES AND UNDAMAGED ITEMS. CONTAINATED DAMAGE-ZEP-FLO DRAIN SOLVENT.  1 QUART (32 OZ.) LID OFF BOTTLE WAS ABSORBED WITH SODIUM BICARBONATE AND SPEEDY DRI-UNTIL PH TAPE READ 7 (NEUTRAL) FINISHED DMP PROCEDURE PER U.P.S. HAZARDOUS MATERIALS PROCESS. ZEP-SHOULD TAPE LIDS CLOSED AND PACK ALL LIQUID BOTTLES IN ENCLOSED PLASTIC BAGS.
